title: Filament Spool Holder that fits Creator Pro

description.text:
Here is an alternate spool holder that fits the Flashforge Creator Pro and allows the use of many different size spools.

How this came to be: Many filament sellers or websites do not list the spool dimensions and I ended up with 4 or 5 spools of specialty filament I could not use with the default spool holders on my creator pro, so I designed these to solve that problem. I could have just designed the 3/8 holder first, but I didn't realize that the one filament I wanted to use was on a spool with smaller hub, so here are both of the designs.

The concept is to print the base but instead of using lots of support, just cut and insert a wood dowel as the shaft the spool rests on. I made two designs, one for 1 inch dowel and the other for 3/8 inch dowel.

They are press fit, but best technique is to push the dowel in from the back rotating back and forth until flush, then remove and push the down in from the front. Enjoy!

description.text:
One of two fully parametric project boxes, one with 4 screws to attach the lid, and one with 6 screws, for larger boxes. Otherwise the designs are identical. The lid has a lip which fits inside the bottom walls. These designs are public on Onshape.com. The links are:
4-hole box: goo.gl/ZdkVYM
6-hole box: goo.gl/v9E0Rr
You can view the designs, and copy them into your own Onshape workspace to modify them.

The parameters are:

Width, Length, Height: overall outside dimensions
LidHeight: Height of the lid portion, not including the lip on the lid
WallThickness: thickness of all six walls (top, bottom, 4 sides)
CornerRadius: radius of the four corners
LidFaceRadius: Radius of fillet around the face of the lid
BottomRadius: Radius of fillet around the bottom face
Clearance: used between the lid screw bosses and the bottom screw bosses, and also between the lip and the bottom inside edge
LipHeight: amount the lip (and lid bosses) extend below the bottom edge of the lid
LipThickness: wall thickness for the lip
HoleInset: distance the screw holes are inset from the outside edges
LidHoleID: ID for screw clearance hole thru lid
LidBossOD: diameter of the lid bosses
BotBossID: diameter of hole in bottom bosses. Set this to hold a sheet metal screw or thread insert if one is used
BotBossOD: diameter of the bottom screw bosses
CornerBraceWidth: width of the braces from the bosses to the walls on the bottom piece
BotBossHoleDepth: blind hole depth of the screw holes in the bottom screw bosses

Note: for most 3D printers, the face fillet radii need to be small, as these features are not well reproduced on a 3D printer.

It's intended that a copy of this box would be used as the basis for a specific project box design, adding holes and other features needed by the project.

description.text: EasyMaker is a hybrid CNC mill and 3d printer. To be more accurate, it's a modular creation robot! The first two modules are an extruder module and a mill module. Others are possible! It has a very large print area, is faster than a Prusa, is easy to build with just a couple of hex wrenches, and currently mills wood and plastic. It uses only 3 motion motors instead of the typical 4. It can be upgraded to 4 motors for milling stronger materials. You can learn about it at peerbhairobotics.com/easymaker/. This is an Advanced Alpha prototype. This is very much a thing in progress!

There are quite a lot of assembly steps to build this. These instructions are rough at this time. EasyMaker is very easy to build -- if you get all the parts, you can figure out what goes where. I had a friend blind build one as a test, and it took him only a couple of hours to figure it out. If you put something in the wrong place, it becomes obvious that it can't work that way. The only difficulty is in initial calibration. Make sure everything is very well squared before using it. EasyMaker can go pretty fast as a 3d printer -- limiting factor is the extruder. I've done tests to the extruders limit at 90mm/s, and it could easily go faster if the extruder could handle it. I think the limit will be around 200 mm/s or so, but don't have an extruder that can reliably handle that speed yet. As a mill, it's designed around a relatively weak spindle. Light woods, plastics, and circuit boards only. A FordHam carving kit with the 44T spindle should also work, but I don't have it, and haven't tested it. With the fordham in place and the system configured to screw drive using 8mm precision screw from Misumi, I believe light aluminum work is possible -- again, untested.

  • Cut the plastic parts. 1/4" Polycarbonate is probably your best material. Acrylic will work, but mars and cracks. It's prettier, but less functional. If you have access to the right tools, make the plastic parts out of 1/8" aluminum. The large XZ plate, which is the largest plastic plate, should be made out of U-channel if you can. This removes the need for the re-enforcement strips. The plastic parts are laid out for a 384x384 mm sheet.

  • Cut the wooden parts out of 1/8" birch plywood. The DXF file is laid out for a 790x384 wood sheet. Other woods should work, as should MDF. 1/8" polycarbonate should also work. These parts are much longer than the others, and I worry about cost. I chose wood to keep it cheap. You can choose other materials if you like them better. The Main build plate is not heated in this design. You can replace it with borosilicate and motorcycle handle-warmers for heat, or use a heated print bed. The print-bed is much larger on this bot than a RepRap, so you'll need a beefy power supply to heat the bed.

  • You'll need a hot-end, electronics, a rotary tool or router of some sort, and mounts. I've designed thing 19062 previously, and this will work to mount a Proxxon micromot 50 series. The 50EF is probably the better choice than the pure 50, since it gives you a dial for speed control. I have not yet designed mounts for other rotorary tools, but any ShapeOko mount will work on this bot as well.

  • The wooden plates DXF file includes a mount for a Wade's extruder that will work with this bot or a ShapeOko mill, but not the support piece for the hot-end. Those should already be on thingiverse, and I just used one I already had laying around. The Piece used to mount a hot-end to a prusa will work fine here -- that's what I used.

  • All 1/4" pieces are mounted with 12mm long M5 screws, with a 1mm M5 washer and T-Slot nuts. Misumi nuts are the cheapest I know of at this time. Almost all screws are M5, unless otherwise specified.

  • All 1/8" pieces use 8mm screws.

  • Printed pieces use either 8mm or 20mm screws. The screws to mount the MXL belt to the large XZ plate are 20mm long.

  • The re-enforcement strips use 30mm long screws. You'll need 4.

  • The MakerSlide wheels are mounted with 55mm long screws. You'll need 4.

  • The Pillow Bearings are 12mm bearings -- McMaster sells them, as does VXB. VXB is much cheaper.

  • The Rods are 12mm thick, 406mm long. 400 should work fine, as should 500. I recommend 500, as it gives you room to expand, and its cheap. You can go longer if you like --I think it can expand to 4 feet in any direction and still work as a printer. It likely is limited to 2 feet to function as a mill. You'll need to increase the thickness of the rod, mounts, and bearings to go larger than that. This design can scale to pretty much any size. Just make sure to get thicker rods and longer misumi rails. McMaster sells the rods at a good price. You can also buy 30-inch long rods and cut them from VXB. Get them plated with either chrome or black ceramic to extend the life in such a dusty environment.

  • The Misumi rails: 2x HFS5-2040-600 , 2x HFS5-2040-375 ( I think 400 would be better. Haven't tried it on my bot, but 375 is the maximum height that fits in my trunk.). 4x HFS5-2020-341, 1x HFS5-2040-365.

  • 1x MakerSlide rail, 375mm long. 4 Dual bearing v wheels.
    • You can laser-cut the Z EndStop Mount, but it has to be very thin and flexible, but not too flexible material. The Z End Stop mount is used to mount a micro-switch to the makerslide Z beam. It must be thin and flexible, so that the switch will engage, but have some flex if you give it bad G-Code. A thick part will damage the MakerSlide wheel, or break itself. A thin part will flex, then bind. Exactly the behavior you want in case you made a GCode error. I re-uploaded the PlasticParts.dxf file -- I forgot a couple of plates. Here's the full costed BOM:
    https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0Av2V6ATJOX9PdFUtbU1FaUQyazRuYkFTMUNkejJKaUE

description.text:
This is a collapsable clamp on LED desk lamp. I used 5630 LED strips, and cut them into 3 150mm strips. I used 20mm 3M screws to connect the pieces and added a toggle switch and and DC jack for power. You can use multiple arm pieces to make it taller, I have even made an optional arm piece that could have more LED strips added to as well. I personally have not used the second light arm yet. Also note that the power box is glued on, once I had soldered and tested the connections I used acrylic solvent to weld it on. This is still a work in progress and needs some refinement, feel free to modify it!

Here are some of the parts I used, I had a few already lying around the house like the toggle switch and power adapter:

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01339G2F6/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o09_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

https://www.amazon.com/20Pcs-5-5mm-2-1mm-Female-Connector/dp/B00UBWP692/ref=sr_1_12?ie=UTF8&qid=1493760534&sr=8-12&keywords=dc+jack

https://www.amazon.com/SPDT-Mini-Toggle-Switch-250V/dp/B00XP5FZ4S/ref=sr_1_5?s=hi&ie=UTF8&qid=1493761289&sr=1-5&keywords=mini+toggle+switch

Printer:

Tevo Tarantula

I printed the Nuke Lamp by MaximFilms (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:19478) in 50% scale and wanted it to have an inside LED with on/off switch. So I made a simple stand for the Nuke Lamp, where you can put a battery. Switch on by sticking the LED wires in the stand. Switch off by sticking the wires in the stand, but the other way around.
Enjoy!

Print the nuke_light_stand with your desired infill (I used 20%, which still was plenty). Use at least 2 perimeters or you most likely will see the battery when printing with a bright material. Fold a little paper spring, put it in one half of the stand, put the battery above it, close the stand and put some tape around it. Done.
Alternatively, you can print nuke_light_stand_left_right_connect two times and maybe omit the tape. But I must warn you, I did not try this, it was just an idea. It might be to fragile. The holes have 2mm radius and the cylinders have 1.9mm.
Feel free to change the pk2 files, if you need a different size or want to change something.

description.text:
Adjustable filament spool holder for the Flashforge Creator Pro. Rather than having a bunch of different spool holders for different brands of filament, I created one spool holder that is adjustable and fits all filament brands I have tried so far.

This project requires some hardware. The spool holder runs on bearings and is very smooth. There's a pdf and a jpg image of the BOM with detailed descriptions of the parts you need. All these are easy to get at a local hardware store.

For the bearings, Fast Eddy Bearings is a great website to get all sorts of bearings. While you can get the metric hardware at your local hardware store, MrMetric is a great source for metric hardware.

http://www.fasteddybearings.com/
http://www.mrmetric.com/

Parts are easy to print. The most challenging bits are the M3 nut slots on the upper bracket and the M8 nut slot on the wing knob. The lower bracket needs a small amount of support for the hole, but it comes away really easy.

The spool holder is quite sturdy due to the M8 screw going through the lower bracket. The STL files are sized such that bearings can be pressed in pretty easy with a simple vice, but depending on your printer settings you may have to play with this a little.

title: Max v3 Rostock Effector for Dual-Mount Titan Aero's

description.text:
This is a prototype effector for the SeeMeCNC Max v3 Rostock.
Should be able to mount two Titan Aero Direct Drive extruders to it. Have not tested it, but it is very easily printable. I printed mine in black Ultimaker Nylon with a raft.

Included in the file set some offsets for the nozzles, estimated from the positions of the models using markers and TinkerCAD's rulers at midpoints.
L X: -19.95 Y: 7.76
R X: 16.95 Y: 2.76

Measured from each of the three effector mounts, The center point of the effector is also marked with a crosshairs.

You can the model in TinkerCad, the placement of the two direct drives is a mirrored solution and their relation follows closely the specifications detailed on E3D's wiki page here: https://wiki.e3d-online.com/wiki/Titan_Assembly#Mirrored_Titan

In Nylon, this weighs 52 grams. The motors should each weigh 140 grams, and the titan Aeros weigh ~108 grams each. Total should be ~548 grams, or nearly half a kilogram. In pounds, that is 1.2lb.

I hope that is enough information. Let me know if you'd like to know more.

https://www.tinkercad.com/things/83Wgmd1Kg3r-titanaero-effector-dual-mount

Edit 05/04/2017: The outer connections aren't placed far enough out for the stock arms. The stock arms are bulky, and can't handle an outside flush mount like the model currently has. I didn't want to reprint the entire thing, so I took a M3x20mm socket caps, a flat washer and some nuts as spacers to create enough space . I'll take a picture later, but be forewarned, the three outboards need to be moved outwards a bit for the arms to be able to reach them.

Edit 05/18/2017: Uploaded a new model. It is more successful at mounting to the arms. More secure, less sway. I drilled holes in the nylon on the bottom for the stock layer fans using a 5/64" drill bit. Do it in ventilation. One of the layer fans has a longer one than the other, that should go to the front side, you'll see. Stock fans fit with no modification.

Edit 05/26/2017: Here is a firmware version using Repetier Firmware 0.92.9 . I had to modify several sections, but if you hook everything up in the same way that I did, it should do fine. Extruder fans turn on when the extruders are above 50F. Layer fans are controlled as normal.

Edit 10/13/2017: Added a small model for mounting a Mini IR Differential leveling sensor. Upgrading my printer to the Duet Wifi board, and including this sensor. The mount will mount right at the center cross of the platform. Will add pictures soon.

title: M5 Partial Thread Bolt With Flat Spot for Condac's Geared Bowden Extruder

description.text:
Pretty much title. I didnt want to buy a bolt, I didnt want to have to grind a flat spot on it, and I didnt want to mess with getting the right thread length.

When putting on the extruder gear, align the set screw with the flat spot. It will never slip. Im not sure what pitch the regular bolts have, so I went with M5*1.5mm which prints well even with uncooled PLA. The nut is also included.

Enjoy.

Note: Tolerances are tight. It kind of has to be, when you think about it. If you absolutely cannot get it to fit, let me know. The extruder I made this for isnt super popular so im not sure a single person will even use this, so i wont go through the trouble if i dont have to.

description.text:
I originally posted this with another spinner I created. I felt like it should be two separate uploads so here it is.
I wanted a spinner that didn't have exposed outer weights.
I also wanted a design so kids could spin them easier, so they have a smaller diameter.
This design will either accommodate 3/4" X 3/16" button magnets or three pennies.
I like using magnets because you can use them to make each other spin, stick to fridge, etc.
To insert the weights just pause at the corresponding layer at the top of the magnets or pennies in each hole.
I did not include spinner caps because there are already plenty of good designs.
You can get the magnets at most craft stores, I picked up a 52 pack at Walmart for $6.

Tips:
Do not use supports otherwise your holes will get filled up.
Depending on your software use the option to not cross the outline for travel movements.
This keeps the holes free and clear of any strands of stray filament.
If you look at the pictures I paused right before layer 31 to get the magnets in place.
But this will change depending on what settings you use.
If you have questions let me know.
